/*
Approach : 
(i) For a fixed start and end index, we only need to do the calculation for a single day as that determines
how much happiness the person will get. We can determine all the happiness values for a fixed pair start and end
by the following formula
     happiness[end] - k + happiness[start]
    This can be done easily by using the concept of sliding window which can calculate the sum and the maximum sum in
O(1) time.

(ii) Now, we have to determine all the possible start and end indices for this. This can be done by using the concept
of a doubly ended queue. The dq will store the start and end indices in descending order based on the happiness value.
So, at each point we have the maximum start and end indices possible in the dq which are possible in this particular
start index of the queue. So we can just pop all the indices from the back of the dq which are smaller than or equal
to this start index of the dq because it is not possible to have larger start indices for any end index with the same happiness.

Then we can pop all the end indices from the front of the dq which are smaller than the current end index of this iteration.

Then, we add this to the maximum answer which is maintained and the front of the dq has the end index which gives the
maximum happiness after k days for this start index. Then, we do the same for the next start index which is the index
just before this start index in the dq.

(iii) At the end, we return the max value.
*/
#include<bits/stdc++.h>
#define ll long long
using namespace std;
class Solution {
